{"id":"2303.00741","submitter":"Guglielmo Marchese","authors":"Guglielmo Marchese, Francesco Macheda, Luca Binci, Matteo Calandra,\n  Paolo Barone and Francesco Mauri","title":"Born effective charges and vibrational spectra in super and bad\n  conducting metals","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Cooperative phenomena like superconductivity and charge-density wave arise\nfrom the interaction between electrons mediated, e.g., by the electron-phonon\ncoupling. The same interaction mechanisms produce strong collision rates in the\nnormal phase of correlated metals, causing a sizeable reduction of dc\nconductivity and reflectivity. As a consequence, low-energy excitations like\nphonons, crucial for materials characterization, become visible in optical\ninfrared spectra. A quantitative assessment of vibrational resonances requires\nthe evaluation of dynamical Born effective charges (BECs), that quantify the\ncoupling between macroscopic electric fields and lattice deformations. We show\nthat the BECs of metals crucially depend on the collision regime of conducting\nelectrons. In particular, we describe, within a first principles framework, the\nimpact of electron scattering on the infrared vibrational resonances, from the\nundamped (collisionless) to the overdamped (collision-dominated) regime. Our\napproach enables the interpretation of vibrational reflectance measurements of\nboth super and bad conducting metals, as we illustrate for the case of strongly\nelectron-phonon coupled superhydride H$_3$S.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 1 Mar 2023 18:54:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 2 Mar 2023 13:22:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-03"}
