{"id":"2303.01057","submitter":"G. S. Krishnaswami","authors":"Govind S Krishnaswami and Ankit Yadav","title":"Bifurcation cascade, self-similarity and duality in the 3-rotor problem","comments":"20 pages, 42 figure files","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"nlin.CD math-ph math.DS math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The three-rotor system concerns equally massive point particles moving on a\ncircle subject to attractive cosine potentials of strength $g$. The quantum\ntheory models chains of coupled Josephson junctions. Classically, it displays\norder-chaos-order behavior with increasing energy $E$ along with a seemingly\nglobally chaotic phase for $5.33g \\lesssim E \\lesssim 5.6g$. It admits pendulum\nand breather families of periodic orbits at all energies. Here, we study\nfamilies of periodic orbits that are born at stability transitions of pendula\nand breathers. The breather family displays one reverse fork-like\nperiod-doubling bifurcation in its rotational regime. Remarkably, pendula\ndisplay geometric cascades of isochronous and period-doubling bifurcations that\naccumulate from both the librational and rotational phases at the common energy\n$E = 4g$. The new family of periodic orbits born at each of these forward\nfork-like bifurcations is found using a novel search algorithm starting from a\nperturbation to the pendulum orbit along a transverse eigenvector of its\nmonodromy matrix. The graphs of stability indices of various classes of newly\nborn orbits meet at $E = 4g$ forming 'fans'. The transitions in the librational\nand rotational phases are related by an asymptotic duality between bifurcation\nenergies and shapes of newly born periodic orbits, which are captured by\nsolutions to a Lam\\'e equation. We also find analogs of Feigenbaum constants\nfor self-similarity in (a) stability indices of librational and rotational\npendula and (b) shapes of the newly born librational orbits as $E \\to 4g$.\nFinally, we argue that none of the infinitely many families of periodic orbits\nwe have found is stable for $5.33g \\lesssim E \\lesssim 5.6g$, providing\nevidence for global chaos in this energy band.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 2 Mar 2023 08:28:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-03"}
